{"paragraphs": ["Okay, let's see. I need to find Dave's average speed for the entire ride. Hmm, average speed isn't just the average of the two speeds, right? I remember that when dealing with average speed for different distances, you have to use the total distance divided by the total time. So maybe I should calculate the total distance he rode and then figure out how long it took him in total.", "Alright, so the problem says Dave rode 30 miles at 10 mph and then 10 miles at 30 mph. Let me break this down. First part: 30 miles at 10 mph. To find the time he took for that part, I can use the formula time = distance divided by speed. So 30 miles divided by 10 mph. That would be 3 hours. Makes sense, because if you go 10 miles every hour, 30 miles would take 3 hours.", "Second part: 10 miles at 30 mph. Again, using the same formula, time is distance over speed. So 10 divided by 30. That gives 1/3 of an hour. Converting that to minutes would be 20 minutes, since 1/3 of an hour is 60 minutes divided by 3. Yeah, that checks out.", "Now, total distance. He rode 30 miles plus 10 miles, so that's 40 miles total. Total time is 3 hours plus 1/3 hour. Let me add those. 3 is the same as 9/3, so 9/3 + 1/3 = 10/3 hours. So total time is 10/3 hours.", "Average speed is total distance divided by total time. So 40 miles divided by (10/3 hours). Dividing by a fraction is the same as multiplying by its reciprocal, so 40 times 3/10. Let me compute that: 40 divided by 10 is 4, times 3 is 12. So 12 mph. Wait, that seems a bit low, but let me check again.", "Wait, 30 miles at 10 mph takes 3 hours. 10 miles at 30 mph takes 1/3 hour. Total time is 3 + 1/3 = 10/3 hours, which is approximately 3.333 hours. Total distance is 40 miles. So 40 divided by (10/3) is indeed 40 * 3/10 = 12. Yeah, so 12 mph. Hmm, that seems correct.", "But let me think again. If he went equal distances, the average speed would be the harmonic mean. Wait, but here the distances aren't equal. He rode 30 miles and 10 miles. So it's not the same as two different speeds for the same distance. So in this case, since the distances are different, we need to compute the weighted harmonic mean. But maybe the way I did it already accounts for the weights because I used total distance and total time. So yes, that should give the correct average speed.", "Alternatively, maybe I can check using another method. Let's consider the formula for average speed when two different speeds are traveled for different distances. The formula is (d1 + d2) / (t1 + t2). Which is exactly what I did. So, since d1 is 30, d2 is 10, t1 is 3, t2 is 1/3, total distance 40, total time 10/3, so 40/(10/3)=12. So that's right.", "I guess another way someone might get confused is if they thought to take the arithmetic mean of the two speeds, which would be (10 + 30)/2 = 20. But that's not correct because he spends different amounts of time at each speed. Since he spent more time at the lower speed, the average speed should be closer to 10 than to 30. But 12 is actually even lower than the harmonic mean. Wait, let's see.", "Wait, harmonic mean is used when the distances are the same. For example, if he went 10 mph for a certain distance and 30 mph for the same distance. Then average speed would be 2/(1/10 + 1/30) = 2/(4/30) = 15. But in this case, the distances are different. So harmonic mean isn't directly applicable here.", "But in our calculation, the average speed is 12 mph. Let's verify again.", "Time for first part: 30 miles /10 mph = 3 hours. Time for second part: 10 miles /30 mph = 1/3 hour. Total time: 3 + 1/3 = 10/3 \u2248 3.333 hours. Total distance: 40 miles. So 40 divided by 10/3 is 12. So that's correct. So the average speed is 12 mph. Therefore, the answer should be 12. I think that's right. I don't see any mistakes in the calculations."]}

